We Need to Talk About Emissions

Templar was built on the principles of transparency, community, and shared ownership.

The people who help create the protocol have every right to own it. As a consequence, Templar miners are some of its largest holders and the fabric that binds the community.

However, time has passed, and a new dynamic has emerged.

Miner sell pressure has become unsustainable, especially for a protocol that is pre-revenue. Everyone has a scheling point, and it's only so long before we start to dwindle as a community.

This forces us to rethink our initial assumptions.

The "community" has evolved, and we must recalibrate.

Moving forward, We will be burning 80% of miner emissions, as we do not require that much compute given the current model size. This decision is based on the assumption of miners running H200×8 machines.

We will calibrate this percentage as model size increases, warranting additional compute.

It's important to note that while we are comfortable with "number go down," many miners who built this with us are not. We have spoken to most of the miners (who requested this change), and they recognize the need to protect our values.
